{
    "analysis": "From the previous metric analysis (using full-series global P95/P05 thresholds computed correctly before window filtering) we scanned 35 (cmdb_id,kpi) pairs for the five candidate services and found 20 pairs with anomalies inside the incident window. The most severe anomaly is ts-route-service diskio (severity ~52x), indicating a massive disk I/O spike starting at timestamp 1706101680. Other notable anomalies include increased latencies on ts-train-service, ts-travel-service, ts-order-service, and CPU and workload increases on ts-travel and ts-train. Many anomalies share the same earliest anomaly timestamp (1706101680), i.e., at the start of the incident window. This suggests either a simultaneous problem affecting multiple services or a root cause in one service propagating downstream. Per rules, we should now use trace analysis to identify call relationships and the most downstream faulty service among the metric-flagged services.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using trace.csv, do the following (compute global thresholds using the full available series before filtering):\n1) Compute global P95 and P05 for each (cmdb_id, trace_name) pair present in trace.csv and report total_count, global_p95, global_p05 (limit to top 50 pairs if many).\n2) Filter trace.csv to the incident window 2024-01-24 13:05:01 to 2024-01-24 13:35:01 UTC. For each (cmdb_id, trace_name) pair where either the trace_name or the cmdb_id contains any of these service names: [\"ts-auth-service\",\"ts-order-service\",\"ts-route-service\",\"ts-train-service\",\"ts-travel-service\",\"root\"], produce an anomaly summary using the global thresholds: anomaly_count_in_window (value >= P95 or value <= P05), earliest_anomaly_ts (integer), max_value_in_window, min_value_in_window, and severity defined as max_value_in_window/global_p95 for high-side anomalies or global_p05/min_value_in_window for low-side anomalies (choose larger if both).\n3) Return only pairs with anomaly_count_in_window > 0, sorted by severity descending, limited to top 20. Also include a small summary: total trace pairs scanned (for the listed services) and number flagged anomalous.\nReturn a JSON-serializable dict with keys: 'trace_thresholds', 'trace_anomaly_summary', 'summary_counts'. Keep outputs compact (only requested fields)."
}

{
    "analysis": "From metric analysis we scanned the five candidate services and found 20 anomalous (cmdb_id,kpi) pairs in the incident window. The single largest metric deviation is ts-route-service diskio (severity ~52x, earliest anomaly at 1706101680), indicating an extreme disk I/O spike coincident with the start of the incident window. Trace analysis shows widespread row_count spikes across many services (root, ts-travel2, ts-train, ts-route, ts-auth, ts-basic, etc.) with very large severity values — however trace row_count spikes indicate increased request counts but do not by themselves identify which service is the originating faulty component. According to the rules, when multiple service-level faults exist we should identify the most downstream faulty service within traces; but if a single component's resource KPI shows an extreme deviation (>>50%) it is a strong candidate root cause. Currently ts-route-service disk I/O stands out as the most significant deviation and aligns with trace anomalies involving route and downstream services. To confirm and to narrow reason (resource type), we need to inspect logs for the candidate services — especially ts-route-service — to see if logs show disk-related errors or other corroborating evidence.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using log.csv, for the candidate services [\"ts-auth-service\",\"ts-order-service\",\"ts-route-service\",\"ts-train-service\",\"ts-travel-service\"] do the following (compute global thresholds using the full available series before window filtering):\n1) For each (cmdb_id, log_name) compute global P95 and P05 and total_count.\n2) Filter log.csv to the incident window 2024-01-24 13:05:01 to 2024-01-24 13:35:01 UTC. For each (cmdb_id, log_name) produce an anomaly summary where anomaly is value >= P95 or value <= P05 using the previously computed global thresholds. For each flagged pair return: cmdb_id, log_name, total_count, global_p95, global_p05, anomaly_count_in_window, earliest_anomaly_ts (integer), max_value_in_window, min_value_in_window, severity (max_value_in_window/global_p95 or global_p05/min_value_in_window, choose the larger if both).\n3) Return only pairs with anomaly_count_in_window > 0, sorted by severity descending, limited to top 20. Also return a small summary: total log pairs scanned for the candidates and number flagged anomalous.\nReturn results as a JSON-serializable dict with keys: 'log_thresholds','log_anomaly_summary','summary_counts'. Keep outputs compact (only requested fields)."
}

